The Eastern Desert: Trade Corridor Assessment

Bureau of Eastern Routes, Tariff and Oversight Division
Filed under: Desert Corridor, Route Instability, Keeper Legacy

Midgaard's eastern trade corridor stretches toward the oasis
settlements and the ancient pyramid worksites. Our caravans have
traveled these routes since before the First Stone Accord, and our
ledgers record every toll paid, every convoy lost, and every
jurisdiction that rose and fell along the way.

We recognize the Keepers of Measure. Their methods -- road stones
set to star angles, cistern basins graded by seasonal drift, caravan
levies assessed in water rights -- are the methods of
proto-bureaucrats. Their Measure Script achieved an administrative
density our own clerks study with professional admiration. If Midgaard
had been built in sand instead of stone, we might have written in
Measure Script ourselves.

The charter road system is deeply familiar. Charter stones bearing
distance, toll rates, and witness seals -- this is infrastructure
we understand. Our own Oath of the Counted Step descends from the
same administrative instinct that built those roads.

What concerns us is the collapse. When the Iseth Reach dried, the
entire legal architecture failed. Water courts became war tribunals.
The Charter Wars erupted as armed factions enforced claims at
spearpoint. Our Bureau watched from the corridor's western terminus
as an orderly system disintegrated. Reaver confederates now operate
with the procedural habits of consumed institutions: seizure
inventories, stamped claim-slates, ritualized convoy inspections
that parody the charter law they replaced.

The Jackal Synod -- militarized funerary priesthoods controlling
shrine-cistern nodes -- represents institutional capture at its
worst. Our Reckoning faction notes, uncomfortably, that Midgaard's
own Tithe of Last Burdens followed a similar logic before reform.

Current assessment: eastern corridor severely degraded. Reliable
toll agreements extend only to the first oasis cluster. Beyond that,
caravan masters negotiate ad hoc passage fees with whatever authority
holds the next water source. Route predictability: low.

The Last Sand Regent -- issuing decrees to a dead bureaucracy from
the deepest observatory strata -- is a phenomenon our clerks discuss
in whispers. A policy engine with royal memory. The Continuity
faction sees a cautionary abstraction. The Reckoning faction sees
a mirror.
