The Eastern Desert -- Sand-Sea Carters' Guild Corridor Report

The Sand-Sea Carters' Guild calls the Eastern Desert what it is:
the overland corridor that keeps this port alive. Every manifest
that crosses our Ledger House counters began its journey somewhere
in that waste, measured and attested by systems older than Mafdet.

The Keepers of Measure were the first attestation authority on the
continent. Their obelisk lines were verification infrastructure:
road stones calibrated to star angles, cistern basins graded by
season, levies assessed in water rights. Their Measure Script
encoded direction, time, volume, and legal status in a single glyph.
Our Dual-Attestation Protocol descends from that principle. One
measurement is an observation. Two measurements are an attestation.

The charter road system is the desert's spine. Charter stones
bearing distance, toll rates, and witness seals are the direct
ancestors of our Ledger House manifests. When a Carter brings goods
from the oasis corridor to the Saltglass Reach, the chain of custody
should run unbroken to our Shoreward Conversion slab. In practice,
it rarely does.

The Charter Wars broke that chain. When the Iseth Reach dried,
water courts became war tribunals. The reaver confederates who
survived maintain procedural habits -- seizure inventories, stamped
claim-slates -- but these are predatory attestation, documentation
stripped of legitimacy and used for extraction.

Our Harbor Wardens classify desert-origin cargo in three trust
categories. Green seal: full charter provenance, witness-attested.
Amber seal: partial documentation, plausible but unverified.
Red seal: no provenance, conflicting stamps, or reaver handling.
Red-seal cargo enters the Quarantine Ledger. We do not refuse it
outright. We simply require it to prove itself.

The Jackal Synod controlling shrine-cistern nodes charges for
water access but issues no documentation our Ledger Houses recognize.
Goods passing through Synod territory arrive with a provenance gap.
The Guild factors that gap into pricing.

The desert taught us our trade. The Keepers measured. The Salt Ledger
Kingdoms documented. The charter roads formalized. When it all
collapsed, Mafdet inherited the obligation to keep measuring,
even when the interior could not.

